{"id":14881061,"mediaExerciseId":"98393fbd-687a-4331-953f-25638af44065","exerciseName":"12","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":612313,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":234,"solutions":[{"id":5968427,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This task asks **to determine the approximately real rate and the exact real rate following the given data.**\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Changing in the buying condition, how much you can pay with your currencies is the **real return rate**. This return does contain a percent of inflation.\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/b28934f014f6c481aa6e2a23602d6109/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/b28934f014f6c481aa6e2a23602d6109/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Given that:\n\n| | | \n|--|--| \n|Nominal rate |4.7% | \n|Inflation rate |2.2% | \n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/02fc3fb22684b3eb45f1ec28a254c62c/lateximg_large.png","width":1007},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/02fc3fb22684b3eb45f1ec28a254c62c/lateximg.png","width":505}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"To calculate the approximately real interest rate, we have to substruct the inflation rate by nominal rate. If we apply this with the given data, we will get the following result.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{apr real rate}&=\\text{nom. rate}-\\text{inf. rate}\\\\[15pt]\n&=4.7\\%-2.2\\%\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\boxed{2.5\\%}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n**The approximately real rate is 2.5\\%.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":408,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/0302eb7851a8d3cb1508c7636caa4fee/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":206,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/0302eb7851a8d3cb1508c7636caa4fee/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"To calculate the exact real rate, we will use the Fisher effect. The Fisher effect tells us the correlation between the nominal return, real return, and rising prices(inflation). Investors are always willing to invest in a security with a positive actual return. The only way for the investor to invest in the negative return of a bond will be in the time of deflation. The formula for the Fisher effect is as follows:\n\n$$1+\\text{R}=\\left(1+\\text{r}\\right)\\times\\left(1+\\text{h}\\right)$$\n\nR- the nominal return\nr- the real return\nh- inflation effect","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":342,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/698f1ba49c84bdc1d6d6000a258be35e/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":172,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/698f1ba49c84bdc1d6d6000a258be35e/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's insert the given data in the formula previous formula.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n1+\\text{r}&=\\dfrac{\\left(1+R\\right)}{\\left(1+\\text{h}\\right)}\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\dfrac{1+4.7\\%}{1+2.2\\%}-1\\\\[15pt]\n&=0.02446\\times100\\\\[15pt]\n&=2.45\\%\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n**The exact real rate is 2.45\\%.**\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":476,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/d9679354d5db43bc37ded0fe0f3cb93c/lateximg_large.png","width":785},"regular":{"height":240,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/d974487fa4c49292a238a10dff56aff5/d9679354d5db43bc37ded0fe0f3cb93c/lateximg.png","width":392}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"259fd331-8e28-4a6f-9717-bace72b2756e","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881062,"exerciseName":"13","page":234,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"ed20c6fc-86e6-466a-9ba3-a9671779f1b4","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-questions-and-problems-13-ed20c6fc-86e6-466a-9ba3-a9671779f1b4"},{"id":14881063,"exerciseName":"14","page":234,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8d2ea01e-9d33-44a8-8064-f5792a392e1d","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-questions-and-problems-14-8d2ea01e-9d33